==English==

===Etymology 1===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|earh}}, {{term|arwe|ārwe}}, from {{proto|Germanic|arhwō}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|arku-|bow and/or arrow}}.  Near cognates include Gothic (arƕazna) and Old Norse ''[[ǫr]]''; further cognates include Latin ''[[arcus]]'', bow

====Pronunciation====
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈaɹəʊ/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæɻoʊ/}}
* {{audio|en-us-arrow.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ærəʊ}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[projectile]] consisting of a shaft, a point and a tail with stabilizing fins that is shot from a [[bow]].
# A [[sign]] or [[symbol]] used to indicate a [[direction]] (eg. <math>\to</math>).
# {{graphtheory}} A [[directed edge]].

